/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

Inbreeding increases the chance of the genes of the parents reappearing massively, obviously. If the parents are gods or royalty, in the mind of the people: "perfect humans", they want to have the best chance of having "perfect" offspring with those same genes. Inbreeding is a way to guarantee that.
Inbreeding also obviously makes the chance of the bad genes reappearing, like hereditary disorders, but in theory two people with flawless genes would only have flawless offspring. Incest doesn't actually lead to random mutations like "common knowledge" seems to think. It leads to less mutation and change.
It makes perfect sense that the most powerful god or the most powerful ruler would only want to breed with someone carrying their genes.

Back then they were basically gods compared to regular people, healthy, beautiful, educated, and most likely like a foot taller and stronger than normal people due to having actually good nutrition growing up and a more stress free lifestyle. No wonder they thought they should keep their "bloodline pure". People didn't know about genetics, but they've always known about certain attributes getting passed down from parents to kids.

>>71839991
>but also something that we don't even suspect might exist
That's part of what I was talking about, I just didn't put it in as clear of terms as you did. By the nature of an object that is intangible and unobservable, it is very likely that we wouldn't even suspect its existence. For example, gravity, there could be some intangible object that causes the force we know as gravity. We cannot observe the object itself, but we can represent its force "gravity" with math. As a result of that, we cannot define any of the attributes of the object that creates the force known as gravity, if it does in fact exist.
>If nobody knows that an object exists, and if it's a complete unknown unknown rather than a known unknown, is it an object?
Yes. But, due to the nature of the object being intangible, it can only be represented in an abstract way, for example, through math, or with some metaphor. So if somehow or another, someone was able to suspect the object existed, there would be no way for them to quantify the object in an objective manner. It would only be able to be represented as a concept or an idea. This is the premise of how theoretical physics works. Theoretical objects that cannot be observed being quantified through mathematics.

I'd say that the feeling of pain is actually objective, but it's a way more complex topic. Let me do my best to explain.

First, let me define consciousness. The explanatory gap prevents us from explaining it but I want to do my best to do it here just so that we know we're talking about the same thing. Lets take the Buddhist idea of reincarnation. Pretty simple, it's the idea that once you die, you start again in another body. But what exactly is reincarnated? It's not your memories since we don't remember past lives. It's not one's personality, interests or opinions. It's clearly something, but we have no way of describing it to other people. We'll call this something "consciousness".

Of course, due to the explanatory gap, we can't prove that our consciousness exists, but we know that it does. One could say that it is self-evident. If we can use this to say that our consciousness is objectively real, we can also say that it is objectively capable of feeling pain. Therefore, the experience of pain is, in a way, objective (we should stop using the words "objective" and "subjective" btw, better words to use would be "real" and "fake" since it's more honest about what objective and subjective really mean)
